<font color="#FF0000">VALUE</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 13  8:29:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Premise:  A lot of the validation that we get in this society comes from our basic cultural upbringing.  My cultural set comes from a background that living in a free society there is a price to be paid.  That price was serving in the military.  It was a honorable thing to do.  My father, grandfather, great grandfather all served. With honor and pride.  Somehow that pride was taken away by the nation that we served.  The service to our country was belittled, discounted, and sometimes spat upon.  The thing that I remember is the statement on the Korean Memorial in D.C. ..  &quot;The price of Freedom is never cheap&quot;..<br><br>
This brings me full circle to REMF's and belittling by other Vets.  There seems to be a thread running throughout all the  groups and meetings around Vietnam.  The statement is &quot;I was in Viet Nam but I didn't do anything&quot;.  So not only do we do it to each other, we do it to ourselves.  What each of us did in country was important and had value.  What each of us did meant something to someone.  This feeling of being &quot;more Vietnam vet than you&quot; disturbs me. And I know for some  it diminishes their desire to post and get feelings out where they can be healed.  I use REMF's as a vehicle to get folks to post where maybe they wouldn't elsewhere.<br><br>
As an example.  Seven years ago, sitting in a group of eight guys, talking about who we were, where we had been, and what we had done.  Discussing our roles in country.  A man in a wheelchair (legs gone below both knees) stated that he was in Viet Nam but &quot;He hadn't done anything&quot;.  Come to find out he was point man and stepped on a mine.  DIDN'T DO ANYTHING????????   Do you see what I am getting at?  What did he have to do to do something?  DIE????<br><br>
Self esteem is important to us all and if we cannot put into  perspective ALL the things that we do in our lives.  What are we expected to do with the one or two years of our lives that have affected us for so long?<br><br>
So I propose that we talk about what we did, establish value to it, and heal.  We may not personally see the value of the jobs that we did.  But others sure can!!  The posts here can put that value to a service that we may think as valueless... and then we buid pride.
